"i guess we all probably hoped for some crazy fruited barrel ages sour or something, given russian river, but we got a very simple and streamlined blonde ale. i get that this is less impressive than what the potential was, but lets call a spade a spade, and admit that this is a fine example of the style, regardless of the price or the makers or anything else. this one is nearly crystal clear, pale yellow, sweet honey colored, with a rising white head that fades as fast as it came up. its a little sweet, more malt middle than expected in the style, maybe could have stood a few more days drying out in fermentation, but i find it flattering here. while the beer is still light in overall stature, its all little more substantive than a lot of blondes, and i respect that. i also dig the yeast, its got some pleasant summer fruit esters that marry into the malt real well, while the finish is still clean. i dont know why all the labels of beer camp beers talk about hops, i didnt find any to be real hoppy, especially this one, which is a little grassy in the finish if anything, but has no bitterness or resins at all. good example of the style if a bit bland next to expectations."
